SIMPLE: repugnant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Repugnant
<hw>Re*pug"nant</hw> <pr>(-n<it>a</it>nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧pugnant</ets>, or L. <ets>repugnans</ets>,
<ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>repugnare</ets>. See
<er>Repugn</er>.]</ety> <def>Disposed to fight against; hostile; at war
with; being at variance; contrary; inconsistent; refractory;
disobedient; also, distasteful in a high degree; offensive; -- usually
followed by <xex>to</xex>, rarely and less properly by <xex>with</xex>;
<as>as, all rudeness was <ex>repugnant</ex> to her
nature</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[His sword] <qex>repugnant</qex> to command.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is no breach of a divine law but is more or less
<qex>repugnant</qex> unto the will of the Lawgiver, God himself.</q>
<rj><qau>Perkins.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Opposite; opposed; adverse; contrary;
inconsistent; irreconcilable; hostile; inimical.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repugnantly</ent>⟦br⟧
